While an experimental vaccine appears to be able to reduce the mortality of Ebola, there are currently no medicines that have been proven to be effective in treating existing infections.
A cocktail of antibodies, ZMapp, initially seemed promising, but formal studies showed that it, in terms of preventing deaths, had fewer advantages than expected.
In the PALM-Study, ZMapp was used as a control, i.e. the scientists used it as a baseline and compared the three other treatments with it.
USA Gymnastics supports the letter of the U.S. Olympic Committee and accepts it as an absolute necessity that the Olympic family advocates for a safe environment for all of our athletes.
We agree with the statement of the USOC that the interests of our athletes and clubs and their sport are better served if we within our organization promote sensible changes, rather than decertification.
USA Gymnastics supports an independent investigation that could bring to light how abuse in the magnitude described by survivors of Larry Nassar was able to go undetected for so long, and welcomes all necessary and appropriate changes.
USA Gymnastics and the USOC have the same goal - to make gymnastics and other sports as safe as possible for athletes so they can pursue their dreams in a safe, positive and self-determined environment.
During the 1960s, Brzezinski worked as a consultant for John F. Kennedy as well as for the government around Lyndon B. Johnson.
During the elections in the year 1976 he advised Carter in foreign policy and then served from 1977 to 1981 in succession to Henry Kissinger as national security advisor (NSA).
As national security advisor, he supported Carter in the diplomatic handling of world affairs such as the Camp David Accords of 1978, the normalization of relations between the United States and China in the late 1970s, the Iranian Revolution, which led to the hostage crisis in Iran in 1979, and the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan in 1979.
